#: /mnt/c/Users/etrees/Desktop/private/spring-framework/framework-docs/modules/ROOT/pages/integration/email.adoc:223
msgid ""
"In your typical enterprise application, though, developers often do not "
"create the content of email messages by using the previously shown approach "
"for a number of reasons:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: /mnt/c/Users/etrees/Desktop/private/spring-framework/framework-docs/modules/ROOT/pages/integration/email.adoc:225
msgid "Creating HTML-based email content in Java code is tedious and error prone."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: /mnt/c/Users/etrees/Desktop/private/spring-framework/framework-docs/modules/ROOT/pages/integration/email.adoc:226
msgid "There is no clear separation between display logic and business logic."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: /mnt/c/Users/etrees/Desktop/private/spring-framework/framework-docs/modules/ROOT/pages/integration/email.adoc:228
msgid ""
"Changing the display structure of the email content requires writing Java "
"code, recompiling, redeploying, and so on."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: /mnt/c/Users/etrees/Desktop/private/spring-framework/framework-docs/modules/ROOT/pages/integration/email.adoc:234
msgid ""
"Typically, the approach taken to address these issues is to use a template "
"library (such as FreeMarker) to define the display structure of email "
"content. This leaves your code tasked only with creating the data that is to "
"be rendered in the email template and sending the email. It is definitely a "
"best practice when the content of your email messages becomes even "
"moderately complex, and, with the Spring Framework's support classes for "
"FreeMarker, it becomes quite easy to do."
msgstr ""
